<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-226-101 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 846 577</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 4 1991 v25 n5 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-tech battlefield. (Persian Gulf War includes many computerweapons and surveillance systems)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As the Persian Gulf War continues, US military commanders aresurprised by the resiliency of Iraq's military communicationsnetwork, which is withstanding considerable bombing by the UScoalition attackers.andP;  The US bombing missions are dependent onadvanced, sometimes old, computer systems for targeting sites inIraq and for interfering with Iraqi defensive fire.andP;  As of lateJan, 1991, the US military claims to have destroyed or disabledone-third of Iraq's command, control and communicationsfacilities.andP;  Redundancy and careful positioning evidently preservemuch of Iraq's network.andP;  Communications cables link many Iraqicommand posts housed in underground concrete bunkers.andP;  Iraq alsouses small ground-level satellite dishes to transmit information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Communications EquipmentComputersMilitary.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>